result.execSummary:
The defendant Wendy J. Happel was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Intentionally Imp.Outside Animal Shelter, a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 951.14(2)(b)1.
  • Mistreatment of Animals. This is not a criminal offense and results only in a money penalty for this offense.

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

3:33 pm case called. Defendant Wendy J. Happel in court with attorney Ludwig L Wurtz.  Scott C. Blader appeared for the Waushara County. Court goes over motion regarding non-compliance with order from 8/25/26 order. Statement by DA Blader regarding motion. Statement by Attorney Wurtz. Futher statement by DA Blader regarding non-compliance by the defendant. Attorney Wurtz calls Joanne Bird, witness sworn, testimony given. DA Blader questions witness. Court makes statement regarding order of 8/25/16. Court extends the agreement for a period of 2 years. Court further orders by December 1, 2016 defendant is to provide to the Court a bill of sale for each of the five animals. By December 1st and by July 1st of each year the defendant is to provide the court with an on-site veterinarian report that the horses have been inspected and been found in good health & are safe.  Court does not require coggins. Provided there are no other horses on the property where these horses are being boarded-coggins will not be needed. Court requires the horses be boarded with Bruce Schultz. Court questions defendant if she understands the order of the court. Defendant states she understands.

Case called @ 1:58 p.m. Defendant Wendy J. Happel in court with attorney Ludwig L Wurtz.  Scott Blader appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Ct 3 only - Defendant advised of minimum/maximum penalty.  Plea QN reviewed w/Defendant. Plea colloquy entertained.  Collateral consequences explained.  Consequences explained for failure to abide by terms of Deferred Sentencing Agreement. Chapter 950 compliance addressed.  Plea: Ct 3 - NC. Court accepts plea and enters JOC. Cts 2 & 4 - DRI.  Court accepts terms and conditions of Deferred Sentencing Agreement.  Matter stayed for 12 months. The Court reminds the defendant that the bond remains in effect throughout the pendency of the Deferred Sentencing Agreement. The Court amends the conditions of bond - Defendant is prohibited from obtaining or boarding any animals other than the following - 3 large horses named Poetry, Foxy & Missy, 1 pony named Penny and 1 mini horse named Freddy which are boarded with R & I Linstedt.  

Ct 1 - Upon motion of the State the Court amends Ct 1 to Mistreatment of Animals contrary to Waushara Co ordinance 26-1(c)(1)(ii).  Plea: NC. Court accepts plea and enters JOC. Court orders: Costs w/ 60 DTP or PP.
